The paper deals with the performance analysis of a communication scheme, specifically Random Linear Network Coding (RLNC) and Tunable Sparse Network Coding (TSNC), which are related to information theory (cs.IT) and network communication (cs.NI). The paper also presents an analytical model based on a Markov process, which is a common tool in stochastic processes (cs.SI) and probability theory (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the proposed model in practical scenarios, such as selecting the best density for transmission, which is related to computer engineering (cs.CE).
